'''Ángel Aníbal Guevara Rodríguez''' is a [[Guatemala]]n soldier and politician.<ref>{{cite news|title=Guevara Presidency Drawing Controversy|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=sL1dAAAAIBAJ&sjid=F14NAAAAIBAJ&pg=6800,3511354&dq=%C3%A1ngel+an%C3%ADbal+guevara&hl=en|accessdate=19 January 2011|newspaper=[[Victoria Advocate]]|date=15 March 1982|agency=[[Associated Press]]|page=3A}}</ref>  He was born in [[La Democracia, Escuintla]] in 1924.

Having served as [[Ministry of Defence (Guatemala)|defense minister]] in the previous administration, Guevara was victorious in the 7 March [[Guatemalan presidential election, 1982|1982 presidential election]] to succeed outgoing [[President of Guatemala|President]] [[Fernando Romeo Lucas García|Romeo Lucas]], who had hand-picked him as his successor. The election was, however, widely denounced as fraudulent by both [[Left-wing politics|left-wing]] and [[Right-wing politics|right-wing]] groups. A [[Military of Guatemala|military]]-led [[coup d'état]] two weeks after the election prevented Guevara from assuming power and instead installed a three-man [[Military dictatorship|junta]] headed by Gen. [[Efraín Ríos Montt]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Guatemala Regime Ousted In Army Coup; Junta Rules|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=iYBQAAAAIBAJ&sjid=TxIEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6630,4235368&dq=%C3%A1ngel+an%C3%ADbal+guevara+coup&hl=en|accessdate=19 January 2011|newspaper=[[Milwaukee Sentinel]]|date=24 March 1982}}</ref>

He ran again in [[Guatemalan general election, 1995|1995]] but failed to win much support.

